{"ts":"2026-06-27T06:22:09.641Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing Health Status Logic**\n\nI've been looking closely at the health status display in `app/portal/projects/page.tsx`. Specifically, I am examining the conditional logic used to determine the `StatusBadge`'s state and label. It seems that the component uses the `healthStatus` property to map to various badge states (\"stable\", \"warning\", \"error\"). The expression has multiple ternary conditional operators, let's make sure it is optimized.\n\n\n**Mapping Status States**\n\nI've determined the valid states for `StatusBadge`: `\"active\" | \"warning\" | \"error\" | \"stable\" | \"decoupled\"`. Now, I'm mapping `agent.status` values to these valid states. I've mapped \"active\" to \"active\", \"warning\" to \"warning\", and \"decoupled\" to \"decoupled\". The most recent finding is that \"evaluating\" maps best to \"stable\" based on `StatusBadge` styles, where stable is blue.\n\n\n**Refining State Mapping**\n\nI've crafted a safe state mapping function, `getBadgeState`, to handle different agent statuses within `app/admin/ai-operations/page.tsx`. This function elegantly translates statuses like \"evaluating\" to \"stable,\" ensuring consistency with the `StatusBadge`'s styling. I've also verified that the current usage of `<StatusBadge` is at `app/admin/ai-operations/page.tsx:896`. This reduces the likelihood of introducing bugs during status state mapping.\n\n\n**Synchronizing Visual Cues**\n\nI've confirmed there's only one `<StatusBadge>` call in the file. Now I'm considering the detail panel's status display. The header currently uses a fixed \"active\" color. Shouldn't this color dynamically reflect the selected agent's status? The intent is to make the dot and text in the detail panel header more visually consistent with the selected agent's state, improving user understanding.\n\n\n**Updating Visual Details**\n\nI'm now focused on refining the detail panel header. The goal is a more dynamic and informative header, moving beyond a static \"active\" state. I'm exploring how to make the header's status dot and text reflect the selected agent's current state. I see that the header currently uses a fixed text and color. I'm reviewing the existing header code again, focusing on lines 1060-1115 to find the text.\n\n\n**Refactoring Status Display**\n\nI'm now implementing the dynamic color change for the detail panel header's status dot, focusing on the selected agent's status. I've introduced a `getStatusDotColor` function that maps status values to specific colors, such as \"active\" to emerald and \"evaluating\" to blue. I plan to use this function to conditionally set the background color of the dot in the detail panel, improving visual feedback.\n\n\n"}}
